<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-06-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-06-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="26" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">McCormick</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-06-03"><hi rend="italic">June 3,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 46.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The President having been advised that the
                            Government of Austria-Hungary is about to be represented in the United
                            States by an ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary, he has, under
                            authority conferred upon him by the Congress of the United States <pb facs="0111" n="31" xml:id="pg_31"/> and in recognition of the
                            friendly intention of the Austro-Hungarian Government, appointed you, by
                            and with the advice and consent of the Senate, to be ambassador
                            extraordinary and plenipotentiary of the United States to
                            Austria-Hungary.</p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>